  "prompt": "How does a half moon happen?",
  "response": "A half moon, also known as a **first quarter** or **third quarter** moon, occurs when the Moon is positioned at a 90-degree angle relative to the Earth and the Sun. This happens during the Moon's orbit around the Earth. Here's how it works:\n\n1. **Moon's Orbit**: The Moon orbits the Earth approximately every 29.5 days (a lunar month). As it moves, the amount of the Moon's illuminated side visible from Earth changes, creating the different phases.\n\n2. **Sun-Earth-Moon Alignment**:\n   - During a half moon, the Moon is **90 degrees** from the Sun in the sky.\n   - This means only **half of the Moon's surface visible from Earth** is illuminated by the Sun, while the other half is in shadow.\n\n3. **Types of Half Moons**:\n   - **First Quarter Moon**: This occurs when the Moon has completed about one-quarter of its orbit around Earth. The right half of the Moon is illuminated.\n   - **Third Quarter Moon**: This occurs when the Moon has completed about three-quarters of its orbit. The left half of the Moon is illuminated.\n\n4. **Why It Happens**:\n   - The Moon does not produce its own light; it reflects sunlight.\n   - The angle at which the Sun's light hits the Moon and the Moon's position relative to Earth determine how much of the illuminated side we can see.\n\nIn summary, a half moon occurs because only half of the Moon's visible surface is illuminated by the Sun when the Moon is at a 90-degree angle to the Earth and Sun. This happens twice in a lunar cycle: once during the first quarter and once during the third quarter.",
